HOUSE BILL No. 1020
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
health.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 16-18-2-36.4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
2 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
3 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 36.4. "Birth control", for
4 purposes of IC 16-41-19.4, has the meaning set forth in
5 IC 16-41-19.4-1.
6 SECTION 2. IC 16-41-19.4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
7 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
8 JULY 1, 2026]:
9 Chapter 19.4. Prevention and Treatment: Access to Birth
10 Control Program
11 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "birth control" means the use of
12 a drug, a device, or surgery to prevent pregnancy. The term
13 includes any of the following:
14 (1) Condoms.
15 (2) Prescription drugs and over the counter birth control.
16 (3) Contraceptive devices, including long acting reversible
17 contraceptive (as defined in IC 12-15-47-1).
2026 IN 1020—LS 6091/DI 104

2
1 Sec. 2. The state department, in consultation with local health
2 departments and the office of the secretary of family and social
3 services, shall establish the access to birth control program for the
4 purpose of increasing access for low income Indiana residents to
5 obtain birth control.
6 Sec. 3. (a) The state department shall, as part of the access to
7 birth control program, develop effective ways to distribute birth
8 control to Indiana residents who have a household income of not
9 more than one hundred eighty-five percent (185%) of the federal
10 poverty level.
11 (b) The access to birth control program must include the
12 following measures:
13 (1) Parental consent must be obtained before distributing
14 birth control to an individual who is less than eighteen (18)
15 years of age.
16 (2) Reimbursement for any birth control distributed may not
17 be higher than the Medicaid reimbursement rate for the birth
18 control.
19 (3) An individual who qualifies for and receives birth control
20 under the program may not be required to pay for the birth
21 control.
22 (4) Any birth control that requires a prescription must be
23 obtained through a health care provider with prescriptive
24 authority for prescribing birth control.
25 Sec. 4. The state department may apply for any state or federal
26 funding, grants, or programs available for the implementation and
27 administration of the access to birth control program.
